subsection.p:
As we saw in , many linear models y = f (x) have equations of the form
    \blert{f(x) = (\text{starting value}) + (\text{rate of change}) \cdot x}
The starting value, or the value of y at x = 0, is the y-intercept of the graph, and the rate of change is the slope of the graph. Thus, we can write the equation of a line as
    \blert{f (x) = b + mx}
where the constant term, b, is the y-intercept of the line, and m, the coefficient of x, is the slope of the line. This form for the equation of a line is called the slope-intercept formslope-intercept form.

webwork.pg-code:
$Earthlink = Formula("99+39.95*x");
$DigitalRain = Formula("50+34.95*x");
$FreeAmerica = Formula("149+34.95*x");
$Line1 = PopUp(
  ["?","Earthlink","DigitalRain", "FreeAmerica"],
  2, # index of correct answer; could also just be the correct answer
);
$Line2 = PopUp(
  ["?","Earthlink","DigitalRain", "FreeAmerica"],
  1, # index of correct answer; could also just be the correct answer
);
$Line3 = PopUp(
  ["?","Earthlink","DigitalRain", "FreeAmerica"],
  3, # index of correct answer; could also just be the correct answer
);

ol.li:
We see that the slope of the line is m = \dfrac{4}{3} and its y-intercept is b = -2. We begin by plotting the y-intercept, (0, -2). We then use the slope to find another point on the line. We have
        m = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{4}{3}
        so starting at (0, -2), we move 4 units in the y-direction and 3 units in the x-direction, to arrive at the point (3, 2). Finally, we draw the line through these two points.

solution.p:
\begin{aligned}[t]m \amp = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}
                = \frac{6000 - 3200}{20 - 0}\\
                \amp =\frac{2800}{20}= 140
            \end{aligned}
        The slope-intercept form of the equation, with m = 140 and b = 3200, is 
        y = 3200 + 140x

